<subSubSection id="C33D655D0522621DFCEE3A9EFAF18087" box="[872,1375,2450,2490]" pageId="0" pageNumber="89" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8B9836D60522621DFCEE3A9EFAF18087" blockId="0.[872,1376,2449,2490]" box="[872,1375,2450,2490]" pageId="0" pageNumber="89">
<heading id="D0D081BA0522621DFCEE3A9EFAF18087" box="[872,1375,2450,2490]" centered="true" fontSize="13" level="2" pageId="0" pageNumber="89" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B953EAC40522621DFCEE3A9EFC6E8084" bold="true" box="[872,960,2450,2489]" pageId="0" pageNumber="89">Keys</emphasis>
to the species 
<emphasis id="B953EAC40522621DFB403A9EFB458084" bold="true" box="[1222,1259,2450,2489]" pageId="0" pageNumber="89">of</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C274D550522621DFB733A9EFAF18087" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[1269,1375,2450,2490]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="0" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B953EAC40522621DFB733A9EFAF18087" box="[1269,1375,2450,2490]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="89">Lestes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33D655D0522621CFE3E3AF9FD868BCD" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="90" pageId="0" pageNumber="89" type="multiple">
<paragraph id="8B9836D60522621CFE3E3AF9FBE18B67" blockId="0.[376,1874,2546,2739]" lastBlockId="1.[376,1874,460,752]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="90" pageId="0" pageNumber="89">
The colour pattern of the pterothoracic venter (= pectoral colour pattern of 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB64B270522621DF88F3AF9FDCB8372" author="Calvert, P. P." journalOrPublisher="Ann. Carnegie Mus." pageId="0" pageNumber="89" pagination="73 - 280" part="6" refId="ref5238" refString="Calvert, P. P., 1909. Contributions to a knowledge of the Odonata of the neotropical region, exclusive of Mexico and Central America. - Ann. Carnegie Mus. 6 (1): 73 - 280, pls 1 - 9." title="Contributions to a knowledge of the Odonata of the neotropical region, exclusive of Mexico and Central America" type="journal article" year="1909">Calvert, 1909: 93</bibRefCitation>
) is of great importance for the identification of the Surinam species of 
<emphasis id="B953EAC40522621DFEFF3955FE4E83BC" box="[377,480,2649,2689]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="89">
<taxonomicName id="4C274D550522621DFEFF3955FE7583BC" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[377,475,2649,2689]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="0" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Lestes</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The dark markings of this pattern appear to be identical, or nearly so, in both sexes of the same species. However, aged specimens often have this colour pattern obscured by pruinosity. If a clean-out is possible, the complete pattern will become discernible. Males of all species are rather easily distinguished by differences in shape of the superior caudal appendages (cerci).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFE3F3168FD868BCD" blockId="1.[376,1874,460,752]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
Caution should be taken in using the key since the males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D550523621CFA673168F97C8BB1" authorityName="Hagen in Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[1505,1746,612,652]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sublatus">
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFA673168F9EE8BB1" box="[1505,1600,612,652]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">Lestes</emphasis>
sublatus
</taxonomicName>
Hagen in Selys and 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D550523621CFDDE319AFCF58B83" authorityName="J. Belle" authorityYear="1997" box="[600,859,662,702]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trichonus">
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFDDE319AFCF58B83" box="[600,859,662,702]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">Lestes trichonus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A26057BF0523621CFCE1319AFBB88B83" box="[871,1046,662,702]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">spec, nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, and the female of 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D550523621CFAE1319AF9F98B83" authorityName="J. Belle" authorityYear="1997" box="[1383,1623,662,702]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basidens" status="spec. nov.">
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFAE1319AF9F98B83" box="[1383,1623,662,702]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">Lestes basidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A26057BF0523621CF9E2319AF8BE8B83" box="[1636,1808,662,702]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" rank="species">spec. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33D655D0523621CFC563022F8EE8139" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" type="key">
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFC563022FB548A68" blockId="1.[976,1274,812,853]" box="[976,1274,814,853]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<heading id="D0D081BA0523621CFC563022FB548A68" box="[976,1274,814,853]" centered="true" fontSize="13" level="2" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFC563022FBB68A68" bold="true" box="[976,1048,814,853]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">Key</emphasis>
to 
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFBC93022FB548A68" bold="true" box="[1103,1274,814,853]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">the males</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<key id="FFB661E70523621CFEFC309CF8EE8139" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<keyStep id="30D32E730523621CFEFC309CF8ED8D8F" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFEFC309CF8EF8D70" blockId="1.[376,1876,910,2052]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<keyLead id="30D695E30523621CFEFC309CF8EF8D70" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
1. Small species: abdomen 26-29.5, hind wing 16-19. Inner side of superior caudal appendages with a strong spine-like basal and subapical tooth and a row of minute teeth between them. Pectoral colour pattern shaped as shown in fig. 2 .... ..................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D550523621CFA383729F8EF8D70" authorityName="Calvert" authorityYear="1909" box="[1470,1857,1061,1101]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mediorufus">
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFA383729F9038D70" box="[1470,1709,1061,1101]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">L. mediorufus</emphasis>
Calvert.
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFEFE3754F8ED8D8F" blockId="1.[376,1876,910,2052]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<keyLead id="30D695E30523621CFEFE3754F8ED8D8F" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">- Larger species: abdomen 30-37, hind wing 20-23. Shape of superior caudal appendages different....................................................................................................2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30D32E730523621CFEFE37B0F8ED8C91" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFEFE37B0F8918C75" blockId="1.[376,1876,910,2052]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<keyLead id="30D695E30523621CFEFE37B0F8918C75" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
2 (1). Caudal appendages pale; apical half of superior caudal appendages regularly and strongly curving downward (fig. 15). Pectoral colour pattern only consisting of a posterior pair of dark spots (fig. 4) ......................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D550523621CFA41362CF9278C75" authority="J. Belle, 1997" authorityName="J. Belle" authorityYear="1997" box="[1479,1673,1312,1352]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvatus" status="spec. nov.">
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFA41362CF9278C75" box="[1479,1673,1312,1352]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">L. curvatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A26057BF0523621CF913362CF8918C75" box="[1685,1855,1312,1352]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" rank="species">spec. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFEFE365EF8ED8C91" blockId="1.[376,1876,910,2052]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<keyLead id="30D695E30523621CFEFE365EF8ED8C91" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">- Caudal appendages not pale; apical half of superior caudal appendages not strongly curving downward.......................................................................................3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30D32E730523621CFEFE36BAF8ED8F48" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFEFE36BAF8EE8F7F" blockId="1.[376,1876,910,2052]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<keyLead id="30D695E30523621CFEFE36BAF8EE8F7F" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
3 (2). Inner side of superior caudal appendages without spines of any kind. Pectoral colour pattern with three pairs of dark oblong spots close to ventro-lateral carina (fig. 7) .................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D550523621CFA333516F9278F7F" authority="J. Belle, 1997" authorityName="J. Belle" authorityYear="1997" box="[1461,1673,1562,1602]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edentatus" status="spec. nov.">
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFA333516F9278F7F" box="[1461,1673,1562,1602]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">L. edentatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A26057BF0523621CF9103516F8EE8F7F" box="[1686,1856,1562,1602]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" rank="species">spec. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFEFF3541F8ED8F48" blockId="1.[376,1876,910,2052]" box="[377,1859,1613,1653]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<keyLead id="30D695E30523621CFEFF3541F8ED8F48" box="[377,1859,1613,1653]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">- Inner side of superior caudal appendages with spines.......................................... 4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30D32E730523621CFEFE3572F8EE8139" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFEFE3572F8EC8E00" blockId="1.[376,1876,910,2052]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<keyLead id="30D695E30523621CFEFE3572F8EC8E00" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
4. Inner side of superior caudal appendages with a truncate basal tooth and a subapical row of minute spines (fig. 18); branch of each inferior caudal appendage reaching backward to a point about one-third the way along superior caudal appendage .................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D550523621CFA603419F8EC8E00" authorityName="Rambur" authorityYear="1842" box="[1510,1858,1813,1853]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenuatus">
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFA603419F9078E00" box="[1510,1705,1813,1853]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">L. tenuatus</emphasis>
Rambur
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFEFF344BF8EE8139" blockId="1.[376,1876,910,2052]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<keyLead id="30D695E30523621CFEFF344BF8EE8139" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
- Inner side of superior caudal appendages with a strong acute tooth at base followed by a row of minute spines (fig. 10); branch of each inferior caudal appendage reaching backward to a point about two-thirds the way along superior caudal appendage 
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFCB834D0F9278139" box="[830,1673,2012,2052]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
............................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D550523621CFA4E34D0F9278139" authority="J. Belle, 1997" authorityName="J. Belle" authorityYear="1997" box="[1480,1673,2012,2052]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basidens" status="spec. nov.">
L. 
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFA7234D0F9278139" bold="true" box="[1524,1673,2012,2052]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">basidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A26057BF0523621CF91034D0F8EE8139" box="[1686,1856,2012,2052]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" rank="species">spec. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</key>
</subSubSection>
<subSection id="E2A82F3D0523621FFC463B4EFA588C77" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="91" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" type="key">
<subSubSection id="C33D655D0523621CFC463B4EFAA38154" box="[960,1293,2114,2153]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFC463B4EFAA38154" blockId="1.[960,1293,2112,2153]" box="[960,1293,2114,2153]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<heading id="D0D081BA0523621CFC463B4EFAA38154" box="[960,1293,2114,2153]" centered="true" fontSize="13" level="2" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFC463B4EFB9A8154" bold="true" box="[960,1076,2114,2153]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">Key to</emphasis>
the 
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFB043B4EFAA38154" bold="true" box="[1154,1293,2114,2153]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">females</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33D655D0523621FFEFD3BA8F8928D72" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="91" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" type="key">
<key id="FFB661E70523621FFEFD3BA8F8928D72" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="91" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<keyStep id="30D32E730523621CFEFD3BA8F8ED800C" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFEFD3BA8F8EC81C3" blockId="1.[377,1876,2209,2751]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<keyLead id="30D695E30523621CFEFD3BA8F8EC81C3" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
1. Small species: abdomen 25-28, hind wing 18-19. Pectoral colour pattern shaped as shown in fig. 2 ...................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D550523621CFA4E3BDAF8EC81C3" authorityName="Calvert" authorityYear="1909" box="[1480,1858,2262,2302]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mediorufus">
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFA4E3BDAF91981C3" box="[1480,1719,2262,2302]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">L. mediorufus</emphasis>
Calvert
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFEFC3A05F8ED800C" blockId="1.[377,1876,2209,2751]" box="[378,1859,2313,2353]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<keyLead id="30D695E30523621CFEFC3A05F8ED800C" box="[378,1859,2313,2353]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">- Larger species: abdomen 29-37; hind wing 21-26.....................................................2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30D32E730523621CFEFF3A36F8EA8382" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFEFF3A36F8EC8366" blockId="1.[377,1876,2209,2751]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<keyLead id="30D695E30523621CFEFF3A36F8EC8366" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
2 (1). Abdomen 29, hind wing 23. Antehumeral stripes brassy black and conspicuously large, extending over whole length of mesepisternum and breadthways extending from middorsal carina to a distance from humeral suture of one-third its own width. Sides of pterothorax yellow except for a small metepimeral black spot below. Pectoral colour pattern shaped as shown in fig. 9 ................................ ............................................................................................. 
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFAF5393FF91A8366" box="[1395,1716,2611,2651]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<taxonomicName id="4C274D550523621CFAF5393FF99C8366" authorityName="Hagen in Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[1395,1586,2611,2651]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sublatus">L. sublatus</taxonomicName>
Hagen
</emphasis>
in Selys
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9836D60523621CFEFC3969F8EA8382" blockId="1.[377,1876,2209,2751]" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
<keyLead id="30D695E30523621CFEFC3969F8EA8382" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">
- Colour pattern of female different; antehumeral stripes narrower and not touching middorsal 
<emphasis id="B953EAC40523621CFD5E399BFC978382" box="[728,825,2711,2751]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="90">carina</emphasis>
.....................................................................................................3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30D32E730520621FFEF332DCF8E58BB3" pageId="2" pageNumber="91">
<paragraph id="8B9836D60520621FFEF332DCF8948B61" blockId="2.[373,1871,462,1104]" pageId="2" pageNumber="91">
<keyLead id="30D695E30520621FFEF332DCF8948B61" pageId="2" pageNumber="91">
3 (2). Caudal appendages pale, stout, not conical i.e. not regularly tapering from base to apex (fig. 33). Pectoral colour pattern only consisting of a posterior pair of dark spots (fig. 4) ..................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D550520621FFA443138F92A8B61" authorityName="J. Belle" authorityYear="1997" box="[1474,1668,564,604]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Lestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="2" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvatus" status="spec. nov.">
